{"from": {"id": "100000182091980", "name": "Ljubomir Ljubojevi\u0107"}, "revision": "10152851210837728", "updated_time": "2014-10-22T13:01:33+0000", "created_time": "2014-10-22T13:01:33+0000", "message": "<p>lspci -nnks $(lspci | grep VGA | awk &#039;&#123;print $1&#125;&#039;)</p><p><br />If you change &quot;VGA&quot; part with some other like &quot;Ethernet&quot; you can get info about different device.</p><p><br />Command &quot;lspci&quot; shows all hw devices in the system. <br /></p><p><br /></p><p>First in row is &quot;ID number&quot; that you can use with &quot;-s&quot; switch to print only about that device. <br /></p><p>Switches &quot;-nnk&quot; will show details about all or only selected device including kernel module used. <br /></p><p>So &quot;lspci -nnks &quot; will show you details about specific device.<br /></p><br />", "subject": "Command to show info about hardware device (in this case VGA card) and kernel it uses", "id": "10152851210857728", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/y7/r/8zhNI-VGpiI.png"}